{
  "answer": "One such moment occurs at the poem's close (lines 114b–115), where the caesura in the original Old English text separates a call for human endurance and seeking of divine comfort from the assurance of heavenly stability:\n\n> frofre to fæder on heofonum,[^1]  \n> þær us eal seo fæstnung stondeð.\n\nThe **a-verse** (\"frofre to fæder on heofonum\" — \"comfort from the Father in heaven\") captures the wanderer's grief-stricken turn *toward* God amid earthly loss, while the caesura pauses to mark resolution. The **b-verse** (\"þær us eal seo fæstnung stondeð\" — \"where for us all stability stands\") then delivers the divine perspective of unchangeable permanence, contrasting the poem's prior litany of mutability (exile, death, ruined halls).[^2] This structural break enacts the theological pivot from temporal sorrow to eternal consolation.\n\n[^1]: Unknown, *Old English Elegies*, ch. 11 (*The Wanderer*), [original](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/11-the-wanderer/original/#p-9bd9cc).\n\n[^2]: Unknown, *Old English Elegies*, ch. 11 (*The Wanderer*), [translation](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/11-the-wanderer/translation/#p-5bdc65).",
